transcription.text:
Speaker 1: Thank you for calling Viagra. How can I help you?

Speaker 2: Yeah, I'm trying to find out where my pills.

Speaker 1: Let me help you out. Let's find out where's your pills. Give me one second.

Speaker 2: All right, Marion, can you just confirm your date of birth?

Speaker 1: 9-14-1958.

Speaker 2: Thank you so much. Give me one second. Pull up tracking.

Speaker 1: It's going to be delivered today. It's out for delivery.

Speaker 2: Your mailman. So whatever time your usual mail comes, he'll have it.

Speaker 1: Oh, my U.S. mail. I thought it came from UPS.

Speaker 2: Oh, no. Mailman.

Speaker 1: Well, I ain't working today because it's below Z. It's about 25 below here.

Speaker 2: Oh, my God. 25 below.

Speaker 1: Yeah.

Speaker 2: Oh, hell no. You can't even leave the house.

Speaker 1: Yeah. All you got to do is look at the news. It's cold as hell up here.

Speaker 2: Is it like those videos, you know, where you see people walking in the house and slipping on the ice?

Speaker 1: Yeah. Well, I thank God we ain't got no snow or nothing.

Speaker 2: I mean, we got snow here, but the streets are clear, though.

Speaker 1: That's a plus. Yeah, we got wind.

Speaker 2: Oh, that shit's nasty.

Speaker 1: I wonder how they're delivering mail today.

Speaker 2: I don't know. That's a good question.

Speaker 1: Hold on. Let me pull up the USPS thing again.

Speaker 2: It says it's out for delivery, so it's on the truck.

Speaker 1: Oh, okay.

Speaker 2: That was at 6:15 a.m. today.

Speaker 1: So maybe it got to the – oh, no. It says arrived at the post office today at 6:04 a.m.

Speaker 2: So out for delivery at 6:15 a.m.

Speaker 1: So maybe it's still there and they're going to attempt to deliver it tomorrow.

Speaker 2: Today or tomorrow?

Speaker 1: Yeah.

Speaker 2: If your mail's going out.

Speaker 1: Okay.

Speaker 2: All right.

Speaker 1: That's cool. All right.

Speaker 2: All right. Stay warm.

Speaker 1: All right. I appreciate you.

Speaker 2: No problem. Have a good weekend.

Speaker 1: All right. You too, Mel. Bye-bye.

Speaker 2: Bye.
